TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a= random(1, 10, 1);
$add1= random(1, 10, 1);
$add2= random(1, 10, 1);
$b=$a+$add1;
$c=$b+$add2;

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\[ \int_{$a}^{$c} f(x) - \int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) = \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\]
$BR where a=
\{ans_rule( 10)\}
and  b=\{ans_rule( 10)\}
EOT

$lowerbound=$b;
$upperbound=$c;

ANS(num_cmp($lowerbound), num_cmp($upperbound));

&SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));

$SOL  $BR

First recall the following fact from p.386 of your textbook:
	\[	\int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx + \int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx = \int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx	\]
and therefore we can rearrange it to look like this:
	\[	\int_{a}^{c} f(x) dx - \int_{a}^{b} f(x) dx = \int_{b}^{c} f(x) dx 	\]
$BR

Applying that in this specific context, we find:
	\[
	\int_{$a}^{$c} f(x) dx - \int_{$a}^{$b} f(x) dx = \int_{$b}^{$c} f(x) dx
	\]
Thus we find \(a=$b\) and \(b=$c\). $BR

EOT

